4
00:00:57,963 --> 00:01:01,262
Let's go, Mike, now!

5
00:01:10,141 --> 00:01:11,540
Dad?

6
00:01:14,513 --> 00:01:15,843
Daddy?

7
00:01:16,013 --> 00:01:18,400
I can hardly hear you.

8
00:01:18,450 --> 00:01:22,323
I said your son has gone AWOL.

9
00:01:22,754 --> 00:01:24,712
My son's in Iraq.

10
00:01:25,123 --> 00:01:29,192
Your son was in Iraq, sir.
His unit arrived stateside four days ago.

11
00:01:29,194 --> 00:01:32,229
Soldier, if my son were back,
I'd sure as hell know it.

12
00:01:32,230 --> 00:01:36,000
He has until Sunday to get back
or he'll be listed as absent.

13
00:01:36,001 --> 00:01:39,304
I'm sorry, I have another call.

14
00:01:44,676 --> 00:01:47,270
You have no messages.

15
00:02:12,905 --> 00:02:17,707
Hey, this is Mike. Leave a message.
If I ever get a signal, I'll call you back.

16
00:02:17,709 --> 00:02:26,250
Mike, it's your old man. Heard you're back.
Give me a call when you get a chance.

17
00:02:30,254 --> 00:02:36,026
Think about that. Freedom is on the march,
and we're safer because of it.

18
00:02:36,027 --> 00:02:38,396
Iraq is still dangerous.

19
00:02:38,396 --> 00:02:43,167
It is dangerous because that society
is becoming more free...

20
00:02:43,168 --> 00:02:45,069
... and heading toward democracy.

21
00:02:45,069 --> 00:02:48,072
Analysts say a broader strategy
is at work...

22
00:02:48,073 --> 00:02:52,109
... one that began with the offensive
in the Sunni Triangle city of Samarra...

23
00:02:52,110 --> 00:02:54,441
... earlier this month.

24
00:02:56,981 --> 00:02:58,745
There you go.

25
00:03:00,519 --> 00:03:02,385
You sure that thing's gonna fit?

26
00:03:02,387 --> 00:03:06,479
You gotta trust somebody
sometime, Hank.

27
00:03:18,069 --> 00:03:20,401
- Anyone call?
- Nope.

28
00:03:28,980 --> 00:03:31,115
Fort Rudd, how may I direct your call?

29
00:03:31,115 --> 00:03:35,752
First Sergeant Arnold Bickman,
Criminal Investigations Division.

30
00:03:35,753 --> 00:03:39,557
I'm sorry, sir. I have no one
by that name on base.

31
00:03:39,557 --> 00:03:41,150
Thank you.

32
00:03:47,799 --> 00:03:50,615
Anything you wanna tell me?

33
00:04:05,984 --> 00:04:07,884
Why can't I go with you?

34
00:04:07,885 --> 00:04:09,586
If he's someplace celebrating...

35
00:04:09,587 --> 00:04:12,490
...last thing he needs is his mother
walking in on him.

36
00:04:12,490 --> 00:04:16,526
- I'll call you when I get there tomorrow.
- It's a two-day drive.

37
00:04:16,528 --> 00:04:18,257
For some people.

38
00:04:55,968 --> 00:04:58,034
You don't wanna let it touch the ground.

39
00:04:58,036 --> 00:04:59,560
Okay.

40
00:05:01,572 --> 00:05:04,906
- Where you from?
- El Salvador.

41
00:05:05,142 --> 00:05:08,713
Do you know what it means
when a flag flies upside down?

42
00:05:08,713 --> 00:05:11,882
- No.
- It's an international distress signal.

43
00:05:11,882 --> 00:05:14,151
- No shit?
- No shit.

44
00:05:14,151 --> 00:05:17,053
It means we're in a lot of trouble,
so come save our ass...

45
00:05:17,055 --> 00:05:20,124
...because we don't have a prayer in hell
of saving ourselves.

46
00:05:20,125 --> 00:05:22,660
- It says a lot.
- Yes, it does.

47
00:05:22,661 --> 00:05:24,161
You know how to do it now?

48
00:05:24,161 --> 00:05:26,425
- Oh, yes.
- Good.

49
00:05:32,670 --> 00:05:37,240
This whole concept of "Vote or Die!"
To me the question is:

50
00:05:37,242 --> 00:05:39,175
Are they gonna vote?

51
00:05:39,177 --> 00:05:43,581
Are they gonna leave the bong
long enough to actually vote?

52
00:05:43,581 --> 00:05:45,447
I don't know.

53
00:05:53,257 --> 00:05:54,781
Dad?

54
00:05:56,560 --> 00:05:58,028
Daddy?

55
00:05:58,529 --> 00:06:00,225
Dad?

56
00:06:14,612 --> 00:06:16,637
Dad?

57
00:06:22,187 --> 00:06:24,018
Dad?

58
00:07:03,327 --> 00:07:07,298
A strong low-pressure system will pass
southward across New Mexico tonight...

59
00:07:07,298 --> 00:07:11,000
... bringing with it colder temperatures
and overcast skies.

60
00:07:11,002 --> 00:07:12,992
Go ahead, sergeant.

61
00:07:15,774 --> 00:07:17,660
Thank you, ma'am.

62
00:07:23,648 --> 00:07:25,564
Sergeant Deerfield?

63
00:07:28,452 --> 00:07:30,454
- Hi.
- Thanks. I know you're busy.

64
00:07:30,454 --> 00:07:34,091
I wish you told me you were coming.
I could've made a little more time.

65
00:07:34,091 --> 00:07:36,393
Bet the base has changed a lot
since your day.

66
00:07:36,394 --> 00:07:37,827
- Thanks, corporal.
- Welcome.

67
00:07:37,829 --> 00:07:39,362
What about his buddies?

68
00:07:39,363 --> 00:07:41,507
We asked, of course.

69
00:07:41,966 --> 00:07:44,802
The rest of my guys
just got back from a 72.

70
00:07:44,802 --> 00:07:47,137
I don't wanna seem like
I'm not concerned.

71
00:07:47,139 --> 00:07:50,841
Where they been, it's a miracle
more guys don't blow off for a few days.

72
00:07:50,841 --> 00:07:54,879
Would you mind if I had a look
at his quarters?

73
00:07:54,879 --> 00:07:55,903
No.

74
00:08:02,086 --> 00:08:04,589
- Penning.
- Yes, sarge.

75
00:08:04,622 --> 00:08:07,625
- This is Specialist Deerfield's father.
- Good to meet you.

76
00:08:07,625 --> 00:08:09,225
- Have you heard from Mike?
- No.

77
00:08:09,226 --> 00:08:11,228
He wants to look at his son's quarters.

78
00:08:11,228 --> 00:08:14,165
Certainly, sir. Shortcut's through here.

79
00:08:14,165 --> 00:08:16,399
Me and Mike go back to Bosnia.

80
00:08:16,401 --> 00:08:20,771
He's sure told me
enough stories about you.

81
00:08:20,771 --> 00:08:23,940
- He hasn't called or anything?
- Does that surprise you?

82
00:08:23,942 --> 00:08:27,343
You know better than me,
but I recall Mike showing up for roll call...

83
00:08:27,345 --> 00:08:29,646
...with a collarbone
sticking through his skin.

84
00:08:29,648 --> 00:08:33,017
Long, Ortiez. This is Doc's dad.

85
00:08:33,018 --> 00:08:36,854
- Oh, honored to meet you, sir.
- Good to meet you.

86
00:08:36,855 --> 00:08:37,879
Doc?

87
00:08:38,056 --> 00:08:40,758
A nickname we gave him.
Made no sense.

88
00:08:40,759 --> 00:08:43,059
That's Mike's room there.

89
00:08:43,061 --> 00:08:45,296
You boys have any idea
where Mike could be?

90
00:08:45,297 --> 00:08:46,963
- No, sir.
- Sorry.

91
00:08:46,965 --> 00:08:49,600
- Must be one hell of a woman.
- Yeah.

92
00:08:49,600 --> 00:08:51,302
Good to meet you, sir.

93
00:08:51,302 --> 00:08:58,614
When you hear from Mike, you tell him
to get his butt back here, okay?

94
00:09:01,446 --> 00:09:03,004
Sergeant?

95
00:09:03,715 --> 00:09:06,951
This is Specialist Deerfield's dad.
We've come to look at his bunk.

96
00:09:06,951 --> 00:09:12,590
Roger. I thought you were
someone trying to steal shit.

97
00:09:12,591 --> 00:09:14,225
Is that your room?

98
00:09:14,225 --> 00:09:17,528
Yeah. That's Mike's bunk there.

99
00:09:19,998 --> 00:09:23,129
It was nice to meet you, sir.

100
00:09:25,070 --> 00:09:26,628
Who's that?

101
00:09:27,239 --> 00:09:28,866
We lost a man.

102
00:09:44,322 --> 00:09:45,755
That's your duffel, right?

103
00:09:45,756 --> 00:09:47,190
Yep.

104
00:09:47,359 --> 00:09:55,828
Tried to convince him to take the one
he was issued. It's like talking to a wall.

105
00:10:06,010 --> 00:10:07,543
No photographs.

106
00:10:07,544 --> 00:10:08,909
Sorry?

107
00:10:09,080 --> 00:10:11,914
Mike's always taking pictures
and e-mailing them to me...

108
00:10:11,916 --> 00:10:14,418
...and I don't see any photographs...

109
00:10:14,418 --> 00:10:16,062
...or a camera.

110
00:10:16,888 --> 00:10:20,292
Property theft is a real problem.

111
00:10:21,326 --> 00:10:26,363
- Guess it was the same during your stint.
- Yeah.

112
00:10:26,364 --> 00:10:31,567
You mind if I take this? His mother
gave it to him and I left mine at home.

113
00:10:31,568 --> 00:10:35,739
I'd like to, but I can't
let you remove anything.

114
00:10:35,740 --> 00:10:37,331
I understand.

115
00:10:37,741 --> 00:10:38,868
Okay.

116
00:10:42,681 --> 00:10:46,250
I think New Mexico is a very important
state, and I want to win New Mexico.

117
00:10:46,250 --> 00:10:50,386
I think New Mexico has great
possibilities of better jobs...

118
00:10:50,388 --> 00:10:54,591
... more jobs.
You've got those wonderful...

119
00:10:54,591 --> 00:10:57,327
This phone's been around
some intense heat.

120
00:10:57,328 --> 00:11:01,634
- It's been in Iraq.
- That could do it.

121
00:11:02,232 --> 00:11:03,927
All right.

122
00:11:07,272 --> 00:11:09,759
This is seriously fried.

123
00:11:10,207 --> 00:11:13,769
Let's see. Okay.

124
00:11:13,945 --> 00:11:15,572
Address book.

125
00:11:15,746 --> 00:11:19,316
All right, there's numbers for barracks,
burgers, chicken, Mom...

126
00:11:19,317 --> 00:11:21,615
...pizza, TD's, Ted.

127
00:11:21,786 --> 00:11:23,086
What's TD's?

128
00:11:23,087 --> 00:11:26,690
That's a local joint. Could've been more,
but that's all that's left.

129
00:11:26,691 --> 00:11:31,195
- Okay, thanks. How much?
- You want the media?

130
00:11:31,196 --> 00:11:32,355
Media?

131
00:11:32,764 --> 00:11:34,163
Yeah. Look.

132
00:11:39,937 --> 00:11:41,404
Speed up!

133
00:11:42,307 --> 00:11:44,571
No. This is trash.

134
00:11:48,312 --> 00:11:50,614
Oh, yeah, here we go.

135
00:11:55,120 --> 00:11:56,953
Bonner, take this.

136
00:11:56,955 --> 00:11:59,099
Long, toss the ball!

137
00:12:01,225 --> 00:12:02,658
Historical moment.

138
00:12:02,659 --> 00:12:07,130
The first time one of these kids is gonna
get to touch a real American football.

139
00:12:07,131 --> 00:12:10,692
- That's your son?
- That's Mike.

140
00:12:12,269 --> 00:12:17,173
Yeah! No, you're going this way!
This way!

141
00:12:18,009 --> 00:12:20,510
Hey, that's my ball, you little fuckers!

142
00:12:20,511 --> 00:12:23,379
Hey! Shit.

143
00:12:23,748 --> 00:12:25,078
Fuck.

144
00:12:26,116 --> 00:12:27,817
What's wrong, man?

145
00:12:27,818 --> 00:12:31,754
- Did Ali Baba take your football?
- Turn off the fucking phone.

146
00:12:31,755 --> 00:12:32,812
Any more?

147
00:12:32,956 --> 00:12:36,025
Yeah, but it looks like the rest
of the files are corrupted.

148
00:12:36,027 --> 00:12:39,663
If you want, I have a program at home
that can pull them off.

149
00:12:39,663 --> 00:12:42,832
It's slow, but I could charge you
a hundred flat.

150
00:12:42,834 --> 00:12:46,903
- Can you e-mail them to me?
- Yeah, no problem.

151
00:12:46,904 --> 00:12:49,635
- Thanks.
- Where's TD's?

152
00:12:56,614 --> 00:12:59,158
I'm looking for my boy.

153
00:13:44,028 --> 00:13:46,572
I'm looking for my son.

154
00:13:46,764 --> 00:13:48,230
Good luck.

155
00:13:48,399 --> 00:13:52,129
I need four tequila shots! Four!

156
00:14:35,279 --> 00:14:37,337
What are you doing?

157
00:14:37,414 --> 00:14:40,616
Just looking at some old photos
Mike sent me.

158
00:14:40,618 --> 00:14:42,745
You gonna be okay?

159
00:14:45,623 --> 00:14:50,760
It doesn't make sense.
He wouldn't leave without telling us.

160
00:14:50,761 --> 00:14:52,821
I will find him.

161
00:14:54,599 --> 00:14:56,032
Okay.

162
00:14:58,135 --> 00:14:59,763
Night.

163
00:14:59,937 --> 00:15:01,599
Good night.

164
00:15:33,971 --> 00:15:36,359
I can hardly hear you.

165
00:15:36,807 --> 00:15:39,938
You gotta get me out of here.

166
00:16:04,034 --> 00:16:07,236
Well, she should've known better.

167
00:16:07,238 --> 00:16:09,034
Hold a sec.

168
00:16:11,808 --> 00:16:13,744
- Your son is in the Army.
- Yes, ma'am.

169
00:16:13,745 --> 00:16:15,979
Then you need to see the military police.

170
00:16:15,980 --> 00:16:19,249
They're busy with the war.
I'm trying to check things out.

171
00:16:19,250 --> 00:16:21,884
- You can file a missing person's report.
- Fine.

172
00:16:21,885 --> 00:16:26,222
In which case, you'll need to see
the military police.

173
00:16:26,224 --> 00:16:33,793
How about you let me talk to somebody
that does more than answer a phone?

174
00:16:36,533 --> 00:16:41,437
Sir, I wondered if you could
help me with this...

175
00:16:41,438 --> 00:16:44,573
I don't think you understand.
He loved that dog.

176
00:16:44,575 --> 00:16:47,443
I'm sure he did, ma'am,
but the dog bit him.

177
00:16:47,445 --> 00:16:50,413
- When a dog bites you, what do you do?
- I really don't know.

178
00:16:50,414 --> 00:16:53,450
You tie it up, you give it away,
you might even shoot it.

179
00:16:53,451 --> 00:16:56,753
You don't pick it up by the throat,
wrestle it into the bathroom...

180
00:16:56,754 --> 00:16:59,088
...and drown it in the tub.

181
00:16:59,090 --> 00:17:03,592
That doesn't sound
a little bit strange to you?

182
00:17:03,594 --> 00:17:05,628
Maybe he thought it was more humane.

183
00:17:05,630 --> 00:17:08,432
More humane? It's a Doberman.

184
00:17:08,432 --> 00:17:11,634
He's drowning it right in front of our son
and it's biting him.

185
00:17:11,635 --> 00:17:16,640
And I'm crying for him to stop.
That all sounds humane to you?

186
00:17:16,641 --> 00:17:18,875
Your husband ever threaten you
or your child?

187
00:17:18,875 --> 00:17:20,943
He'd never hurt us. He just needs help.

188
00:17:20,944 --> 00:17:22,913
That's why you need to go to the VA.

189
00:17:22,913 --> 00:17:25,882
You need to go to them
and ask them about counseling.

190
00:17:25,883 --> 00:17:28,250
You think I haven't been down there?

191
00:17:28,251 --> 00:17:31,587
He won't go. He's gonna hurt himself.
I know he is.

192
00:17:31,588 --> 00:17:34,257
- Look, I'd really like to help you here.
- Really?

193
00:17:34,258 --> 00:17:37,426
Oh, because it looks to me
like you don't give a crap.

194
00:17:37,427 --> 00:17:39,195
You know, in fact, I do.

195
00:17:39,197 --> 00:17:42,965
But I gotta tell you, crimes against dogs
are particularly hard to prosecute.

196
00:17:42,967 --> 00:17:45,469
If you don't mind,
I have somebody waiting for me.

197
00:17:45,470 --> 00:17:48,038
- Okay. Fuck you, lady.
- Okay.

198
00:17:48,038 --> 00:17:49,063
Great.

199
00:17:56,780 --> 00:17:59,511
That kind of morning, huh?

200
00:18:01,085 --> 00:18:03,220
You gotta take that to military police.

201
00:18:03,221 --> 00:18:07,990
I'm trying to keep my son
out of more trouble.

202
00:18:07,991 --> 00:18:09,558
I know you're busy...

203
00:18:09,559 --> 00:18:12,863
...but I need you to make one phone call
to his bank and find out...

204
00:18:12,864 --> 00:18:16,232
...if he's made withdrawals or used
his credit card in the last week.

205
00:18:16,233 --> 00:18:18,602
Retired cop, or just watch a lot of TV?

206
00:18:18,603 --> 00:18:20,136
Military police, retired.

207
00:18:20,137 --> 00:18:23,606
Then you should know. Army has
jurisdiction over its own personnel.

208
00:18:23,607 --> 00:18:25,275
Sorry, I hope you find your son.

209
00:18:25,276 --> 00:18:29,145
I don't know what you think your job is,
but if it's anything like mine was...

210
00:18:29,146 --> 00:18:32,883
...it's to roll up drunks, twiddle your
thumbs, not ask too many questions.

211
00:18:32,884 --> 00:18:36,586
But my son has spent the last 18 months
bringing democracy to a shithole...

212
00:18:36,586 --> 00:18:38,221
...and serving his country.

213
00:18:38,221 --> 00:18:41,211
He deserves better than this.

214
00:18:49,200 --> 00:18:56,354
Because we have done the hard work,
we are entering a season of hope.

215
00:18:56,773 --> 00:19:01,611
My God. Hank Deerfield.
I'll be a son of a bitch.

216
00:19:01,612 --> 00:19:04,780
- What the hell you doing at home?
- Well, you almost missed us.

217
00:19:04,781 --> 00:19:07,217
We're taking the camper
to see the grandkids.

218
00:19:07,218 --> 00:19:10,086
- I called you at the base.
- Base?

219
00:19:10,086 --> 00:19:13,957
Well, Christ, Hank.
I've been retired for 14 years.

220
00:19:13,958 --> 00:19:17,294
- You have not.
- Yeah, going on 15.

221
00:19:17,295 --> 00:19:19,429
How in the hell are you?

222
00:19:19,430 --> 00:19:22,132
Fine. Oh, want coffee or a piece of pie?

223
00:19:22,133 --> 00:19:26,403
No, no, I don't have time.
Helen's waiting in the camper.

224
00:19:26,403 --> 00:19:27,903
What'd you do...

225
00:19:27,904 --> 00:19:30,640
...bust an axle and call me for a tow?

226
00:19:30,641 --> 00:19:35,345
No, I was hoping you were still at CID.
I'm looking for a friendly face.

227
00:19:35,346 --> 00:19:39,281
- Neither one of your boys in trouble, I hope.
- No.

228
00:19:39,282 --> 00:19:42,451
- What was that oldest one's name, Darren?
- David.

229
00:19:42,452 --> 00:19:45,888
David, that's right.
Joined 82nd Airborne, didn't he?

230
00:19:45,890 --> 00:19:48,490
- Yeah.
- Yeah, tough bunch of sons of bitches.

231
00:19:48,491 --> 00:19:50,621
How's he liking it?

232
00:19:51,429 --> 00:19:56,132
He died in a helicopter crash
on maneuvers at Fort Bragg 10 years ago.

233
00:19:56,133 --> 00:20:00,002
Oh, God, I'm sorry to hear that, Hank.

234
00:20:00,003 --> 00:20:01,971
Very sorry.

235
00:20:02,940 --> 00:20:04,840
How about the younger one?

236
00:20:04,842 --> 00:20:06,673
- Mike.
- Yeah.

237
00:20:06,844 --> 00:20:10,881
Regular Army, just like his old man.
In Iraq, doing well.

238
00:20:10,882 --> 00:20:15,451
I'm doing a favor for a neighbor lady.
One of her boys is in a little trouble.

239
00:20:15,452 --> 00:20:18,721
Is there anybody we know still there?

240
00:20:18,722 --> 00:20:21,439
No, no. They're all gone.

241
00:20:25,563 --> 00:20:28,230
She got you on a short leash.

242
00:20:28,231 --> 00:20:29,875
Well, you know.

243
00:20:30,701 --> 00:20:33,259
Kids are waiting for us.

244
00:21:15,613 --> 00:21:17,948
I found his old checkbook.

245
00:21:17,949 --> 00:21:22,451
Is there anything written on it?
I need a password.

246
00:21:22,452 --> 00:21:24,820
No, there's nothing on it.

247
00:21:24,821 --> 00:21:25,877
You sure?

248
00:21:26,423 --> 00:21:33,790
Which do you think it is,
I'm blind or I don't feel like telling you?

249
00:21:40,270 --> 00:21:43,038
I'm worried, Hank. I'm truly worried.

250
00:21:43,039 --> 00:21:47,072
He's a good boy. He'll have a reason.

251
00:21:48,546 --> 00:21:49,569
Hank?

252
00:21:50,280 --> 00:21:54,085
I'll find him. Talk to you tomorrow.

253
00:22:23,314 --> 00:22:24,580
What's going on?

254
00:22:24,582 --> 00:22:28,317
Don't you worry, it's not animal-related.

255
00:22:28,318 --> 00:22:29,479
What?

256
00:22:29,653 --> 00:22:32,521
They found body parts
out on Mesa Luna Road.

257
00:22:32,522 --> 00:22:35,497
- I'll get the car.
- Okay.

258
00:22:39,829 --> 00:22:43,233
Hey, Bonner. There's your family.

259
00:22:43,933 --> 00:22:45,535
Stop fucking around.

260
00:22:45,536 --> 00:22:48,971
- You could've fucking broken it!
- You're a fucking idiot.

261
00:22:48,972 --> 00:22:50,098
Oh, fuck.

262
00:22:50,273 --> 00:22:52,142
Oh, shit! What do I do?

263
00:22:52,143 --> 00:22:54,309
Do not stop. Do not fucking stop!

264
00:22:54,310 --> 00:22:57,557
- Speed up! Speed up!
- Bonner!

265
00:23:07,691 --> 00:23:10,766
- Fuck.
- What are you doing?

266
00:23:17,801 --> 00:23:22,036
Maybe go down there a little bit further.

267
00:23:23,173 --> 00:23:26,509
Aaron, I need more evidence markers.

268
00:23:26,509 --> 00:23:28,724
You got all we have.

269
00:23:28,846 --> 00:23:33,650
Straighten out some wire hangers, and buy
Dixie cups to stick on the ends of them.

270
00:23:33,651 --> 00:23:35,448
Come on.

271
00:23:36,220 --> 00:23:38,520
And get me a receipt.

272
00:23:49,834 --> 00:23:51,199
Sean?

273
00:24:03,346 --> 00:24:05,076
Thanks.

274
00:24:40,817 --> 00:24:43,462
Tell me good news, Hodge.

275
00:24:45,288 --> 00:24:49,826
Well, it looks like the victim
was killed by that fire site there...

276
00:24:49,826 --> 00:24:53,630
...then the body was chopped up,
it was burned...

277
00:24:53,631 --> 00:24:56,732
...and animals scattered the parts, so...

278
00:24:56,733 --> 00:24:59,469
And you're smiling
like an idiot because...?

279
00:24:59,470 --> 00:25:03,506
Well, the base bought this field
from the city two months ago.

280
00:25:03,507 --> 00:25:08,411
City property only extends 50 feet
from the center line of the road...

281
00:25:08,412 --> 00:25:12,788
...so I don't think it's our body, chief.

282
00:25:13,983 --> 00:25:16,076
Well, hallelujah.

283
00:25:16,252 --> 00:25:17,881
Let's go home.

284
00:25:19,990 --> 00:25:21,324
Wrap it up, fellas!

285
00:25:21,325 --> 00:25:25,730
Boys with the shiny buttons
are coming in.

286
00:26:09,173 --> 00:26:12,040
It will necessarily break
the back of the insurgency.

287
00:26:12,041 --> 00:26:13,710
It is not, though, the panacea.

288
00:26:13,711 --> 00:26:17,547
Just by taking it out does not mean
the rest of the insurgency will fall.

289
00:26:17,548 --> 00:26:20,549
More than half of Fallujah's
250,000 residents...

290
00:26:20,550 --> 00:26:23,586
... have already fled
in anticipation of the offensive.

291
00:26:23,586 --> 00:26:29,659
Insurgents believed to number in the
thousands have been preparing defenses...

292
00:26:29,660 --> 00:26:34,839
... attacking U.S. Troops,
and rigging booby traps.

293
00:26:44,275 --> 00:26:45,902
Mr. Deerfield?

294
00:26:47,076 --> 00:26:50,876
Jim Osher. Could I get a word?

295
00:26:51,048 --> 00:26:55,337
Yeah, come on in. I'll just be a minute.

296
00:27:31,954 --> 00:27:37,125
Sir, I regret to inform you
that a body was found last night.

297
00:27:37,126 --> 00:27:42,898
Upon investigation, we believe it to be
the remains of your son, Michael Deerfield.

298
00:27:42,900 --> 00:27:46,501
Right. They'll need me
to identify the body?

299
00:27:46,502 --> 00:27:48,388
No, sir. We've...

300
00:27:48,404 --> 00:27:52,008
They've determined identity in other ways.
I believe partial fingerprints.

301
00:27:52,009 --> 00:27:54,676
What do you mean "partial"?
What happened to him?

302
00:27:54,677 --> 00:28:02,161
- I'm not at liberty to say, sir. Someone...
- I wanna see his body now!

303
00:28:24,173 --> 00:28:27,676
Sergeant Deerfield, this isn't necessary.

304
00:28:27,678 --> 00:28:29,778
It's not how you wanna
remember your son.

305
00:28:29,779 --> 00:28:31,269
Maybe not...

306
00:28:31,815 --> 00:28:39,925
...but it's the way he left this earth,
so I don't see as I have any choice.

307
00:28:45,128 --> 00:28:47,663
Working backwards,
carbon patterns show the body...

308
00:28:47,663 --> 00:28:49,731
...was dismembered
before it was burned.

309
00:28:49,732 --> 00:28:53,301
It appears a large knife or tool
was used, but the blade was dull...

310
00:28:53,302 --> 00:28:56,471
...which is why the bones are
shattered rather than severed.

311
00:28:56,472 --> 00:28:59,375
Burn patterns show us
the dismembered parts were stacked...

312
00:28:59,375 --> 00:29:03,011
...and doused with an accelerant in
an attempt to incinerate the body.

313
00:29:03,012 --> 00:29:06,348
You'd need an oven
to approach an effective temperature...

314
00:29:06,349 --> 00:29:09,184
...which means most tissue
would've been left intact.

315
00:29:09,185 --> 00:29:12,721
So the damage is largely the result
of scavengers stripping the bones.

316
00:29:12,722 --> 00:29:15,324
Cause of death will take
more time to determine...

317
00:29:15,325 --> 00:29:17,527
...but there is evidence of stab wounds.

318
00:29:17,528 --> 00:29:18,688
How many?

319
00:29:19,363 --> 00:29:20,660
I'm sorry?

320
00:29:20,931 --> 00:29:24,666
- How many stab wounds?
- Well, with much of the flesh missing...

321
00:29:24,667 --> 00:29:27,869
...we can only count blows
that made impact with bone.

322
00:29:27,871 --> 00:29:30,740
How many of those were there?

323
00:29:30,740 --> 00:29:32,605
Forty-two.

324
00:29:35,179 --> 00:29:37,494
One knife, or several?

325
00:29:39,282 --> 00:29:40,750
One.

326
00:29:48,592 --> 00:29:52,028
- Gonna turn these over to the Army?
- Tried to.

327
00:29:52,028 --> 00:29:59,411
Said they took their own photos.
And they didn't say it in a nice way.

328
00:30:02,138 --> 00:30:05,074
I'd like to give you
a call tomorrow before you go home.

329
00:30:05,075 --> 00:30:06,808
I have a few questions.

330
00:30:06,809 --> 00:30:08,606
Ask them now.

331
00:30:08,778 --> 00:30:12,048
- Your son didn't own a green car?
- Mike doesn't own a car.

332
00:30:12,048 --> 00:30:16,152
Motorist reported seeing a green sedan
parked on the shoulder near the field...

333
00:30:16,153 --> 00:30:17,953
...that Saturday night.

334
00:30:17,954 --> 00:30:22,157
One of the theories is that this is
a carjacking or a robbery gone wrong...

335
00:30:22,159 --> 00:30:25,126
...and there's a big uptick
in gang activity lately.

336
00:30:25,127 --> 00:30:27,762
I wanna see where he died.

337
00:30:27,763 --> 00:30:31,032
I'm sorry. It's an active crime scene,
but I will let you know...

338
00:30:31,034 --> 00:30:34,438
- ...as soon as you can.
- Okay.

339
00:30:35,305 --> 00:30:37,864
What else you wanna ask?

340
00:30:39,108 --> 00:30:41,877
A lot of the deaths like these
have been drug-related.

341
00:30:41,878 --> 00:30:45,347
Are you asking if Mike was
a drug dealer or just an addict?

342
00:30:45,348 --> 00:30:47,048
I don't wanna be asking anything.

343
00:30:47,049 --> 00:30:50,318
You know the Army
does regular drug tests.

344
00:30:50,319 --> 00:30:53,036
Not when they're in Iraq.

345
00:30:54,857 --> 00:30:58,126
Now, we found this
under your son's mattress.

346
00:30:58,127 --> 00:31:00,328
It's not gonna go in my report.

347
00:31:00,329 --> 00:31:02,832
But why I ask is last month...

348
00:31:02,833 --> 00:31:07,103
...we arrested three soldiers who were
trying to smuggle heroin in from Kuwait.

349
00:31:07,104 --> 00:31:10,705
They'd made arrangements to sell it
to a local Mexican gang.

350
00:31:10,707 --> 00:31:12,974
I understand Mike spoke a little Spanish?

351
00:31:12,976 --> 00:31:17,012
And you think he could've been a drug mule
because he spoke Spanish?

352
00:31:17,013 --> 00:31:18,571
No...

353
00:31:18,781 --> 00:31:24,032
...because somebody cut off
his hands and his head.

354
00:32:03,759 --> 00:32:07,148
I'm really sorry about your son.

355
00:32:09,333 --> 00:32:10,993
Show me.

356
00:32:13,502 --> 00:32:15,299
I'm sorry?

357
00:32:17,673 --> 00:32:20,509
I need to see where he died.

358
00:32:20,509 --> 00:32:22,603
It's not our case.

359
00:32:23,012 --> 00:32:25,080
The murder occurred on military property.

360
00:32:25,082 --> 00:32:27,516
- You know where it is?
- There's nothing to see.

361
00:32:27,517 --> 00:32:33,167
Then there shouldn't be any problem
with me seeing it.

362
00:32:39,429 --> 00:32:47,569
You people sure as hell know how to
trample a crime scene, I'll give you that.

363
00:32:53,309 --> 00:32:55,478
I suppose you thought
it was a good idea...

364
00:32:55,479 --> 00:33:01,230
...to have everybody you ever met
park on this shoulder.

365
00:33:03,653 --> 00:33:05,721
If your boys knew
what they were doing...

366
00:33:05,721 --> 00:33:09,557
...they'd have found traces of blood
in the gravel right here.

367
00:33:09,558 --> 00:33:11,661
It's where he was killed.

368
00:33:11,662 --> 00:33:14,329
So you don't see blood,
but you know it's there?

369
00:33:14,330 --> 00:33:15,388
Yeah.

370
00:33:15,932 --> 00:33:20,102
Just like I know his body
was dragged from here...

371
00:33:20,103 --> 00:33:21,626
...to there.

372
00:33:22,005 --> 00:33:24,064
That's remarkable.

373
00:33:24,407 --> 00:33:27,442
The ground is rock-hard,
but you see drag marks.

374
00:33:27,443 --> 00:33:33,115
You go to the trouble to burn a body,
don't you think you'd cover your tracks?

375
00:33:33,115 --> 00:33:35,917
I'm going to the restroom.

376
00:33:40,457 --> 00:33:43,224
You might find it easier
to drive around that field.

377
00:33:43,226 --> 00:33:46,615
You couldn't do any more damage.

378
00:33:52,836 --> 00:33:55,702
Everybody knows everything.

379
00:34:10,152 --> 00:34:11,949
- Hi.
- Hi.

380
00:34:12,121 --> 00:34:14,923
- Can I help you?
- I suppose the MPs have been in here...

381
00:34:14,925 --> 00:34:18,027
...asking questions about
what happened in that field.

382
00:34:18,027 --> 00:34:22,197
- They sure have. Terrible thing.
- I'm checking it out for the family.

383
00:34:22,199 --> 00:34:24,266
Mind if I ask if you saw anything?

384
00:34:24,266 --> 00:34:26,568
I wish we had.
We would've liked to help.

385
00:34:26,570 --> 00:34:29,405
We didn't know what it was
when we smelled it, did we?

386
00:34:29,405 --> 00:34:31,474
- No.
- How's that?

387
00:34:31,474 --> 00:34:34,043
That Sunday,
when we drove in the parking lot...

388
00:34:34,043 --> 00:34:36,878
...we just thought somebody
had been barbecuing.

389
00:34:36,880 --> 00:34:39,849
Smelled like burned meat.

390
00:34:42,251 --> 00:34:43,913
Thank you.

391
00:35:33,103 --> 00:35:36,871
Tell your MP friends they should be
looking for a blue car, not a green one.

392
00:35:36,873 --> 00:35:37,896
Why?

393
00:35:38,074 --> 00:35:41,976
Because a blue car under
a yellow light looks green.

394
00:35:41,978 --> 00:35:43,706
Doesn't it?

395
00:35:57,327 --> 00:35:59,260
It certainly does.

396
00:36:08,170 --> 00:36:09,728
Thank you.

397
00:36:10,239 --> 00:36:13,112
It's the least I could do.

398
00:36:13,510 --> 00:36:16,139
I'd say that's accurate.

399
00:36:29,693 --> 00:36:32,322
I'll get a plane ticket.

400
00:36:32,362 --> 00:36:33,795
No.

401
00:36:35,331 --> 00:36:37,266
What do you mean, "No"?

402
00:36:37,266 --> 00:36:40,202
I'll bring him home soon as I can.

403
00:36:40,202 --> 00:36:44,606
I need to see him.
I need to be with Michael.

404
00:36:44,608 --> 00:36:46,438
He's gone.

405
00:36:46,610 --> 00:36:49,344
I need to be with my boy.

406
00:36:49,346 --> 00:36:51,974
There is nothing left.

407
00:36:54,483 --> 00:36:57,543
What the hell does that mean?

408
00:36:58,688 --> 00:37:02,123
Joanie, for once in your life,
will you take my word for something?

409
00:37:02,125 --> 00:37:04,753
For once? For once?

410
00:37:04,927 --> 00:37:07,563
I seem to remember
me being the one saying no...

411
00:37:07,563 --> 00:37:11,400
...and you saying it'd be good for his
character. Who won that argument, Hank?

412
00:37:11,400 --> 00:37:15,070
Mike was the one who wanted to join.
I sure as hell didn't encourage it.

413
00:37:15,070 --> 00:37:21,510
Living in this house, he never could've
felt like a man if he hadn't gone.

414
00:37:21,510 --> 00:37:26,646
Both of my boys, Hank.
You could've left me one.

415
00:37:37,594 --> 00:37:39,117
Joanie?

416
00:37:43,065 --> 00:37:45,364
Joan, please.

417
00:37:54,945 --> 00:37:59,994
Joanie, I can't sit here
and listen to you cry.

418
00:38:02,351 --> 00:38:04,376
Well, then don't.

419
00:39:00,809 --> 00:39:02,572
Door.

420
00:39:05,748 --> 00:39:07,340
Night.

421
00:39:08,451 --> 00:39:10,280
Night, sweetheart.

422
00:39:40,516 --> 00:39:41,813
Fuck!

423
00:39:48,157 --> 00:39:51,860
Another hallway left. Stacked, on me.
Ortiez, cover this door to the right.

424
00:39:51,860 --> 00:39:54,463
To the right.
Penning, get this door with me. Long!

425
00:39:54,463 --> 00:39:56,130
- Roger!
- Covering!

426
00:39:56,132 --> 00:39:57,690
Got it.

427
00:39:57,967 --> 00:39:59,195
Go, go.

428
00:39:59,402 --> 00:40:01,905
- Clear. Clear.
- Clear.

429
00:40:02,739 --> 00:40:06,675
Give me a status on that door!
Better not fuck around with that phone!

430
00:40:06,675 --> 00:40:09,007
Absolutely not, Bonner!

431
00:40:09,646 --> 00:40:13,121
See how the clothes aren't burnt?

432
00:40:15,385 --> 00:40:17,858
It's really weird, Dad.

433
00:40:18,554 --> 00:40:24,534
- All right, all clear. Let's move it out!
- Move it out.

434
00:40:42,846 --> 00:40:43,869
Sure.

435
00:40:44,047 --> 00:40:46,378
Evie, chicken sandwich.

436
00:41:13,809 --> 00:41:16,054
Mustard or mayonnaise?

437
00:41:17,045 --> 00:41:19,081
No, thank you, ma'am.

438
00:41:19,081 --> 00:41:22,150
A woman stands topless
in front of you...

439
00:41:22,152 --> 00:41:26,213
..."ma'am" could be taken as an insult.

440
00:41:26,588 --> 00:41:28,556
- This your son?
- Yes, ma'am.

441
00:41:28,557 --> 00:41:32,661
I'm asking if anybody saw him.
It would've been a week ago Saturday.

442
00:41:32,661 --> 00:41:38,313
I'm sorry. I don't recognize
anything but the uniform.

443
00:41:38,902 --> 00:41:41,375
Thank you, ma'am. Miss.

444
00:41:49,679 --> 00:41:51,168
Right here.

445
00:42:10,465 --> 00:42:12,228
Stay here.

446
00:42:12,869 --> 00:42:14,936
Excuse me, lieutenant?

447
00:42:14,938 --> 00:42:18,106
I was just wondering how
I came to be assigned this case.

448
00:42:18,106 --> 00:42:19,335
Which case?

449
00:42:19,474 --> 00:42:21,210
Jacob Ronald Millard...

450
00:42:21,210 --> 00:42:24,713
...slaughterhouse employee,
arrested for torturing chickens.

451
00:42:24,713 --> 00:42:26,981
It's no big deal. Everybody does it.

452
00:42:26,983 --> 00:42:29,284
Everybody doesn't poke
their eyes out, asshole.

453
00:42:29,284 --> 00:42:31,253
- Sure, they do.
- Shut up!

454
00:42:31,253 --> 00:42:34,556
Boss doesn't want me
humping his daughter.

455
00:42:34,556 --> 00:42:36,925
Now we're shocked beyond words.

456
00:42:36,925 --> 00:42:39,827
You see how you could draw
information out of people?

457
00:42:39,829 --> 00:42:42,396
People just like you, Emily.

458
00:42:42,398 --> 00:42:47,168
That is how you got promoted from
traffic to detective squad, am I right?

459
00:42:47,170 --> 00:42:48,431
I'm sorry?

460
00:42:48,605 --> 00:42:50,800
Oh, don't be.

461
00:42:50,974 --> 00:42:54,909
If Wayne or Hodge could've fucked their
way into the squad, they would've too.

462
00:42:54,911 --> 00:42:56,411
Well, Wayne would have.

463
00:42:56,411 --> 00:43:00,215
One of us needs to know
what we're doing.

464
00:43:00,215 --> 00:43:03,985
You see, that's what concerns me.
Having fucked my way into the job...

465
00:43:03,987 --> 00:43:08,757
...I may not be qualified enough to piece
together this complex of a crime.

466
00:43:08,757 --> 00:43:10,425
I mean, take that murder site.

467
00:43:10,425 --> 00:43:14,463
I would've never concluded that
that soldier was killed on Army property.

468
00:43:14,463 --> 00:43:18,099
I would've been fooled by the signs
of struggle on the side of the road.

469
00:43:18,101 --> 00:43:22,204
And you know that little trail of broken
brush from there to where he was burned?

470
00:43:22,204 --> 00:43:27,309
Well, that would've made me think he was
killed in our jurisdiction, and then moved.

471
00:43:27,309 --> 00:43:31,346
Because the killers didn't think it smart
to chop him up under a bright streetlight.

472
00:43:31,347 --> 00:43:36,512
Yeah. I would've totally
misread that crime scene.

473
00:43:41,724 --> 00:43:44,425
No, no, no. It's good work.

474
00:43:44,427 --> 00:43:46,862
I mean, we needed another homicide.

475
00:43:46,862 --> 00:43:50,398
What, we've solved three
out of the last 10?

476
00:43:50,400 --> 00:43:53,235
Another unsolved would cement
my standing with the mayor.

477
00:43:53,235 --> 00:43:55,603
You have a problem with
your fellow detectives?

478
00:43:55,605 --> 00:43:58,172
- You feel the need to show them up?
- No, sir.

479
00:43:58,173 --> 00:44:00,409
So it's the military police?

480
00:44:00,409 --> 00:44:03,378
You think they're boobs,
they'll bungle the investigation?

481
00:44:03,378 --> 00:44:07,682
No, but let's not pretend we don't know the
real motives for the Army wanting this case.

482
00:44:07,684 --> 00:44:11,987
Psychic powers.
When did you discover you had these?

483
00:44:11,987 --> 00:44:16,257
You don't believe their primary concern will
be how this incident reflects on the Army?

484
00:44:16,259 --> 00:44:18,260
This is a career move? Is that it?

485
00:44:18,260 --> 00:44:20,795
I don't have a career, sir. I have a job.

486
00:44:20,797 --> 00:44:22,998
I take care of my son
and do what I'm told.

487
00:44:22,998 --> 00:44:25,666
This boy died in a ditch
beside one of our streets.

488
00:44:25,668 --> 00:44:30,005
Someone burned him like a cord of wood,
leaving his remains for animals to chew on.

489
00:44:30,005 --> 00:44:32,807
With respect, if that was your son
just back from Iraq...

490
00:44:32,809 --> 00:44:36,010
...I don't think you'd be as happy
about tossing this case off...

491
00:44:36,012 --> 00:44:38,880
...so you look better come election time.

492
00:44:38,880 --> 00:44:42,217
- That was with respect?
- That was my intent, sir.

493
00:44:42,217 --> 00:44:44,786
Fine. I'll think about it
and I'll let you know.

494
00:44:44,786 --> 00:44:46,722
Every second we lose in this...

495
00:44:46,722 --> 00:44:49,657
Didn't you say that you would do
whatever you were told?

496
00:44:49,659 --> 00:44:53,077
I sometimes exaggerate for effect.

497
00:44:56,898 --> 00:44:58,284
How's David?

498
00:44:59,034 --> 00:45:00,195
Sorry?

499
00:45:00,369 --> 00:45:02,065
Your son.

500
00:45:03,940 --> 00:45:05,606
He's fine, thanks for asking.

501
00:45:05,608 --> 00:45:09,311
That deadbeat ex of yours ever
show up for any of his games?

502
00:45:09,311 --> 00:45:11,913
David's pretty pathetic
at every sport he attempts...

503
00:45:11,914 --> 00:45:14,682
...so he wants as few people
to witness it as possible.

504
00:45:14,684 --> 00:45:17,385
Well, that's a damn shame, isn't it?

505
00:45:17,387 --> 00:45:21,333
It's not like he's the boy's father.

506
00:45:23,992 --> 00:45:26,128
Anyway, way I see it...

507
00:45:26,128 --> 00:45:30,465
...it's the oddballs and the misfits who go
on to do interesting things with their lives.

508
00:45:30,465 --> 00:45:32,800
How many former
high school quarterbacks...

509
00:45:32,802 --> 00:45:36,070
...do we roll into the drunk tank
every Saturday night?

510
00:45:36,072 --> 00:45:38,672
Little misery in school is a good thing.

511
00:45:38,673 --> 00:45:43,110
You know, I was first-string quarterback
in my high school.

512
00:45:43,112 --> 00:45:48,762
I seem to recall you
showing me pictures of such, sir.

513
00:45:53,322 --> 00:45:56,557
You're gonna keep after me
about this Deerfield boy, aren't you?

514
00:45:56,559 --> 00:46:02,108
I think you know what
the right thing to do is, sir.

515
00:46:02,864 --> 00:46:05,356
Jesus H. Christ.

516
00:46:07,269 --> 00:46:08,737
- Hilary.
- Yes, sir?

517
00:46:08,737 --> 00:46:13,989
- Get me Captain Fenderman at the base.
- Yes, sir.

518
00:46:55,083 --> 00:46:58,715
Would you like to sit down, ma'am?

519
00:47:00,989 --> 00:47:02,976
Is that everything?

520
00:47:04,726 --> 00:47:06,827
Is that all of him?

521
00:47:06,829 --> 00:47:08,523
Yes, ma'am.

522
00:47:10,333 --> 00:47:13,835
- You must have to keep that room cold.
- Yes, ma'am.

523
00:47:13,835 --> 00:47:15,860
That looks cold.

524
00:47:20,342 --> 00:47:24,061
I wanna go inside. Can I go inside?

525
00:47:27,382 --> 00:47:29,755
No, ma'am. I'm sorry.

526
00:47:41,329 --> 00:47:44,318
My deepest sympathies, ma'am.

527
00:47:47,269 --> 00:47:50,643
You don't have a child, do you?

528
00:47:51,940 --> 00:47:53,498
Do you?

529
00:49:23,798 --> 00:49:25,967
- Mr. Deerfield?
- Hi.

530
00:49:25,967 --> 00:49:28,536
I heard you ask if you
could have Mike's Bible...

531
00:49:28,536 --> 00:49:31,039
...and I thought it might
bring you some comfort.

532
00:49:31,039 --> 00:49:32,706
Anybody know you took this?

533
00:49:32,708 --> 00:49:37,978
No, sir. I asked the visitors' center
where you were staying and they told me.

534
00:49:37,980 --> 00:49:39,713
Can I buy you a coffee?

535
00:49:39,715 --> 00:49:42,360
I really should get back.

536
00:49:43,686 --> 00:49:45,657
How about a drink?

537
00:50:26,061 --> 00:50:27,791
To Mike.

538
00:50:35,871 --> 00:50:41,177
I need to ask you something.
And I want the truth.

539
00:50:42,911 --> 00:50:44,778
Was Mike doing drugs?

540
00:50:44,780 --> 00:50:47,873
Doc? I guess.

541
00:50:48,583 --> 00:50:53,722
No more than the other guys.
He wasn't like a heavy doper or anything.

542
00:50:53,722 --> 00:50:57,659
You ever see him hanging out
off the base with anyone?

543
00:50:57,659 --> 00:50:59,389
Maybe Mexicans?

544
00:50:59,561 --> 00:51:01,257
No, sir.

545
00:51:04,300 --> 00:51:06,201
How you adjusting?

546
00:51:06,402 --> 00:51:08,233
Being back?

547
00:51:09,472 --> 00:51:11,773
Hasn't been that long.

548
00:51:11,773 --> 00:51:13,675
Call your parents?

549
00:51:13,675 --> 00:51:17,378
My mom. My dad and I aren't close.

550
00:51:19,782 --> 00:51:23,271
- Did you guys talk much?
- Sure.

551
00:51:24,652 --> 00:51:27,211
We could've talked more.

552
00:51:31,293 --> 00:51:33,994
Did he ever say anything to you
that I should know?

553
00:51:33,996 --> 00:51:35,759
No, sir.

554
00:51:36,197 --> 00:51:38,028
I mean...

555
00:51:38,367 --> 00:51:41,135
...you see shit over there
you don't wanna talk about...

556
00:51:41,137 --> 00:51:43,204
...even with your buddies.
- Yeah.

557
00:51:43,204 --> 00:51:45,172
But he did all right, Mike?

558
00:51:45,173 --> 00:51:48,233
He was a first-class soldier.

559
00:51:48,344 --> 00:51:51,346
You know Mike. He loved the Army.

560
00:51:51,347 --> 00:51:58,572
Couldn't wait to get there, save
the good guys and hurt the bad guys.

561
00:52:01,523 --> 00:52:05,960
They shouldn't send heroes
to places like Iraq.

562
00:52:05,960 --> 00:52:08,949
Everything there's fucked up.

563
00:52:09,465 --> 00:52:15,429
Before I went, I'd never say this,
but you ask me now...

564
00:52:16,137 --> 00:52:22,704
...they should just nuke it
and watch it all turn back to dust.

565
00:52:25,681 --> 00:52:26,806
Hank?

566
00:52:28,083 --> 00:52:29,744
You okay?

567
00:52:29,918 --> 00:52:33,253
Yeah, I was just about to call you.

568
00:52:33,255 --> 00:52:36,157
A package came from Michael.

569
00:52:39,061 --> 00:52:41,028
What kind of package?

570
00:52:41,030 --> 00:52:45,699
I don't know, it's a package.
He sent it to himself. It's from overseas.

571
00:52:45,701 --> 00:52:47,135
I'm gonna open it.

572
00:52:47,135 --> 00:52:48,262
No.

573
00:52:48,436 --> 00:52:50,909
What do you mean, "No"?

574
00:52:51,373 --> 00:52:55,677
Does it look like it's been opened
by customs or by the military?

575
00:52:55,677 --> 00:52:59,273
How would I know? No, it doesn't.

576
00:52:59,447 --> 00:53:00,782
Why can't I open it?

577
00:53:00,782 --> 00:53:02,250
Just don't.

578
00:53:02,418 --> 00:53:03,748
Please.

579
00:53:05,387 --> 00:53:08,204
Just put it someplace safe.

580
00:53:10,425 --> 00:53:12,121
Okay.

581
00:53:13,695 --> 00:53:16,027
- Night.
- Good night.

582
00:54:13,621 --> 00:54:15,795
- Morning.
- Morning.

583
00:54:16,090 --> 00:54:18,992
I wonder if I could ask you
a few questions about your son.

584
00:54:18,994 --> 00:54:21,996
- I thought it wasn't your case.
- It sort of fell back to me.

585
00:54:21,996 --> 00:54:24,971
Isn't that our good fortune?

586
00:54:25,000 --> 00:54:27,768
I was wondering if you knew
if your son had any enemies.

587
00:54:27,769 --> 00:54:31,472
You mean other than the thousands
of Iraqis and foreign fighters...

588
00:54:31,472 --> 00:54:33,907
...trying to kill him
till a couple of weeks ago?

589
00:54:33,909 --> 00:54:37,945
Yeah, that shirt looks like it's still wet.

590
00:54:37,947 --> 00:54:39,746
It's dry enough.

591
00:54:39,981 --> 00:54:42,617
Anything bothering him
that you know about?

592
00:54:42,617 --> 00:54:44,016
No.

593
00:54:44,186 --> 00:54:46,721
You looking into the gang connection?

594
00:54:46,722 --> 00:54:50,657
Why? You have reason to think your son
was involved in gangs or drugs?

595
00:54:50,659 --> 00:54:52,126
No.

596
00:54:53,228 --> 00:54:55,862
- When did you last speak to him?
- Why?

597
00:54:55,864 --> 00:54:59,701
Capital One faxed me a recent summary
of his credit-card charges.

598
00:54:59,702 --> 00:55:01,802
After he got back,
he bought tube socks...

599
00:55:01,804 --> 00:55:04,539
I told him a dozen times,
those are the worst socks.

600
00:55:04,539 --> 00:55:07,875
They have no heel,
they wear right through.

601
00:55:07,876 --> 00:55:11,179
And then he went out for some chicken.

602
00:55:11,179 --> 00:55:13,014
Does it say what time?

603
00:55:13,014 --> 00:55:15,159
And no more charges.

604
00:55:15,851 --> 00:55:20,221
We assume your son was killed sometime
Saturday night or Sunday morning.

605
00:55:20,222 --> 00:55:22,824
We haven't found his wallet,
but if it was stolen...

606
00:55:22,824 --> 00:55:27,661
...we'd see a lot more charges on it,
like computers, stereos, what have you.

607
00:55:27,663 --> 00:55:31,724
Have you been to the chicken place yet?

608
00:55:46,815 --> 00:55:50,047
- Enjoy.
- How can I help you?

609
00:55:50,184 --> 00:55:52,954
We're inquiring about a soldier
who was here a week ago.

610
00:55:52,954 --> 00:55:55,722
You're kidding me, right?
We're a block from the base.

611
00:55:55,724 --> 00:55:57,791
Can you tell what time he was here?

612
00:55:57,793 --> 00:56:00,260
It's the last four digits.

613
00:56:00,262 --> 00:56:05,266
1:03 a.m. Sunday morning.
We bill that as Saturday. Anything else?

614
00:56:05,266 --> 00:56:09,103
- Can you tell us what he bought?
- Not without the actual receipt.

615
00:56:09,103 --> 00:56:11,072
Okay. Thank you.

616
00:56:11,239 --> 00:56:15,143
Your four-piece dinner is $6.79.
Is that what most people order?

617
00:56:15,143 --> 00:56:16,744
That or the three-piece.

618
00:56:16,744 --> 00:56:18,610
So with tax...

619
00:56:18,880 --> 00:56:21,610
...$21.77 would be...

620
00:56:22,784 --> 00:56:24,885
...three meals, three people.

621
00:56:24,887 --> 00:56:31,125
Four, if it's the three-piece,
or one really hungry soldier.

622
00:56:57,920 --> 00:57:00,822
There you are.
I just dropped something off for you.

623
00:57:00,822 --> 00:57:03,590
- You did?
- We took statements from Mike's squad.

624
00:57:03,592 --> 00:57:05,059
Thought you'd want them.

625
00:57:05,059 --> 00:57:08,028
That's great. I was gonna call you
to arrange interviews.

626
00:57:08,030 --> 00:57:10,346
Saved you the trouble.

627
00:57:10,632 --> 00:57:12,360
How so?

628
00:57:12,534 --> 00:57:15,302
Sworn statements on your desk.

629
00:57:15,304 --> 00:57:18,972
What, you didn't think
I'd want to interview them myself?

630
00:57:18,974 --> 00:57:21,641
Just trying to give you a leg up.

631
00:57:21,643 --> 00:57:24,411
Thanks. I sort of like to do
my own detective work.

632
00:57:24,413 --> 00:57:26,481
I'll tell you what.

633
00:57:26,481 --> 00:57:27,949
Read the statements.

634
00:57:27,949 --> 00:57:32,820
If you still wanna question them,
I will be glad to take the request to my C.O.

635
00:57:32,820 --> 00:57:34,588
Perhaps you misunderstood me.

636
00:57:34,590 --> 00:57:37,724
It's not a request.
I want the list of the men in his unit.

637
00:57:37,726 --> 00:57:40,628
- On your desk.
- And I wanna interview them this afternoon.

638
00:57:40,628 --> 00:57:42,829
You'll have to go to my C.O.
With that one.

639
00:57:42,831 --> 00:57:46,833
- My chief already spoke to him.
- This one's a bit of a jurisdictional mess.

640
00:57:46,835 --> 00:57:50,538
There is no mess. The murder was
committed in our jurisdiction.

641
00:57:50,539 --> 00:57:53,840
That's where it gets murky. Read those.

642
00:57:53,842 --> 00:57:57,545
I'd be glad to put the request in.

643
00:58:02,684 --> 00:58:06,153
- You don't have the sworn statements?
- I have the statements...

644
00:58:06,155 --> 00:58:08,623
Then they're cooperating.
I don't see the problem.

645
00:58:08,623 --> 00:58:10,992
I have a right to interview
potential witnesses.

646
00:58:10,992 --> 00:58:14,762
- Has the Army said you can't?
- They said they'd consider my request.

647
00:58:14,762 --> 00:58:16,329
And that was 10 minutes ago.

648
00:58:16,331 --> 00:58:19,699
And I'd like to talk to these men
before they've been coached...

649
00:58:19,701 --> 00:58:23,704
...or debriefed so any inconsistencies
in their stories will have disappeared.

650
00:58:23,704 --> 00:58:26,574
Being a former military man,
I'm sure you've seen that...

651
00:58:26,574 --> 00:58:31,846
...perhaps when you served
with Lieutenant Kirklander?

652
00:58:31,847 --> 00:58:33,976
I'll tell you what.

653
00:58:34,115 --> 00:58:37,885
Skip upstairs and cry to your boyfriend.

654
00:58:37,885 --> 00:58:43,092
Because I'm just not in the mood
to give a shit.

655
00:59:24,032 --> 00:59:28,603
We're showing video that has
just come in to CNN from Fallujah.

656
00:59:28,603 --> 00:59:30,333
You ordered yet?

657
00:59:37,945 --> 00:59:39,918
Okay. Dig in, men.

658
00:59:58,532 --> 01:00:00,762
- May I?
- Please.

659
01:00:03,405 --> 01:00:06,641
- Okay. Out.
- No, I can do it.

660
01:00:06,641 --> 01:00:11,375
You can. Now get ready for bed. Go on.

661
01:00:17,853 --> 01:00:20,740
Is there anything I can do?

662
01:00:48,583 --> 01:00:50,483
You're supposed to read it to me.

663
01:00:50,485 --> 01:00:52,952
I don't understand one word of it.

664
01:00:52,954 --> 01:00:55,322
Well, do you know any stories?

665
01:00:55,324 --> 01:00:57,657
I'm not much of a storyteller.

666
01:00:57,659 --> 01:01:00,632
Well, then read me the book.

667
01:01:06,467 --> 01:01:08,668
You know where your name comes from?

668
01:01:08,670 --> 01:01:11,916
- My mother?
- No, before that.

669
01:01:12,139 --> 01:01:15,710
You're named after King David.
Your mother didn't tell you that?

670
01:01:15,710 --> 01:01:17,110
That figures.

671
01:01:22,351 --> 01:01:23,875
All right.

672
01:01:24,318 --> 01:01:28,889
There were two great armies assembled,
the Israelites and the Philistines.

673
01:01:28,889 --> 01:01:31,858
They were both up on hills,
the Valley of Elah in between.

674
01:01:31,860 --> 01:01:34,228
It's in Palestine, you know where it is?

675
01:01:34,228 --> 01:01:35,596
- No.
- Doesn't matter.

676
01:01:35,597 --> 01:01:39,300
Anyway, the Philistines had a champion.

677
01:01:39,300 --> 01:01:42,065
A huge giant...

678
01:01:42,237 --> 01:01:43,981
...named Goliath.

679
01:01:44,039 --> 01:01:46,440
Really? There's a robot named Goliath.

680
01:01:46,440 --> 01:01:48,208
This is a different guy.

681
01:01:48,210 --> 01:01:51,668
So every day, for 40 days...

682
01:01:51,847 --> 01:01:54,715
...Goliath would stride down
into the valley...

683
01:01:54,715 --> 01:01:58,251
...and challenge somebody from the
other side to fight, but nobody would.

684
01:01:58,253 --> 01:02:02,389
All the bravest and strongest warriors
that the king had were all too scared.

685
01:02:02,391 --> 01:02:05,925
- Why didn't they just shoot him?
- They didn't have guns.

686
01:02:05,927 --> 01:02:08,228
They had arrows,
but there are rules to combat.

687
01:02:08,230 --> 01:02:12,699
You don't shoot somebody that's
challenging you to fight with a sword.

688
01:02:12,701 --> 01:02:14,224
So anyway...

689
01:02:14,902 --> 01:02:20,240
...one day this kid, not much bigger
than you, comes delivering bread.

690
01:02:20,242 --> 01:02:22,543
He says to the king, "I'll fight Goliath."

691
01:02:22,543 --> 01:02:24,878
- Really? No way.
- True story.

692
01:02:24,880 --> 01:02:28,416
So the king dresses David
in his own armor.

693
01:02:28,416 --> 01:02:32,452
But it's much too big and heavy,
so David takes it off and he looks around...

694
01:02:32,454 --> 01:02:35,856
...and he finds five smooth stones
about that big.

695
01:02:35,856 --> 01:02:41,394
And he steps out into the valley,
with his slingshot in his hand.

696
01:02:41,396 --> 01:02:43,396
Goliath comes running...

697
01:02:43,398 --> 01:02:45,800
...yelling this horrible scream.

698
01:02:45,800 --> 01:02:48,469
And David lets fly with that slingshot.

699
01:02:48,469 --> 01:02:51,005
Hits him in the forehead,
cracks his skull open...

700
01:02:51,005 --> 01:02:53,807
...Goliath falls down, dead.

701
01:02:53,809 --> 01:02:55,443
So he shot him.

702
01:02:55,443 --> 01:02:58,833
With a rock. Not the same thing.

703
01:03:01,949 --> 01:03:04,952
- And you want to know how he beat him?
- How?

704
01:03:04,952 --> 01:03:09,422
The first thing David had to fight
was his own fear.

705
01:03:09,423 --> 01:03:12,570
He beat that, he beat Goliath.

706
01:03:12,726 --> 01:03:17,565
Because when Goliath came running,
David planted his feet, took aim and waited.

707
01:03:17,565 --> 01:03:20,768
You know how much courage that took?

708
01:03:20,768 --> 01:03:26,505
Just a few more steps
and Goliath would've crushed him.

709
01:03:26,574 --> 01:03:29,878
Then he let fly with that rock.

710
01:03:30,679 --> 01:03:33,614
That's how you fight monsters.

711
01:03:33,614 --> 01:03:37,418
You lure them in close to you,
you look them in the eye...

712
01:03:37,418 --> 01:03:39,820
...you smack them down.

713
01:03:41,121 --> 01:03:43,090
You fight a lot of monsters?

714
01:03:43,090 --> 01:03:44,318
Yeah.

715
01:03:44,626 --> 01:03:46,253
You win?

716
01:03:46,728 --> 01:03:49,028
If I didn't, I'd have been crushed, right?

717
01:03:49,030 --> 01:03:50,554
Yeah.

718
01:03:51,199 --> 01:03:53,030
Okay, then.

719
01:03:54,135 --> 01:03:55,396
Good night.

720
01:04:09,351 --> 01:04:11,619
He likes to sleep with that door open.

721
01:04:11,619 --> 01:04:13,248
He'll be okay.

722
01:04:23,565 --> 01:04:25,362
Door!

723
01:04:32,503 --> 01:04:35,302
- Not that much.
- Okay.

724
01:04:37,307 --> 01:04:38,693
That's good.

725
01:04:55,092 --> 01:04:57,161
You know that story isn't true.

726
01:04:57,161 --> 01:04:59,376
Of course it's true.

727
01:05:00,030 --> 01:05:02,574
It's even in the Koran.

728
01:05:05,335 --> 01:05:09,940
- May I read the men's statements?
- There is nothing in them that'll help.

729
01:05:09,940 --> 01:05:18,355
The last time any of the men saw Mike was
Saturday afternoon, before he left base.

730
01:05:25,923 --> 01:05:28,224
You're a good father.

731
01:05:29,293 --> 01:05:32,963
You don't have to prove you loved him.

732
01:05:32,963 --> 01:05:35,125
I'm sure he knew.

733
01:05:54,585 --> 01:05:56,143
Dad?

734
01:06:00,458 --> 01:06:02,152
Daddy?

735
01:06:06,697 --> 01:06:09,114
Something happened, Dad.

736
01:06:34,425 --> 01:06:36,893
It's the second day
of what the U.S. Military...

737
01:06:36,894 --> 01:06:41,644
... is now calling
the "New Dawn" in Fallujah.

